ad chronological and geographical scope, this book deepens our understanding of the material and mechanical conditions of historical operatic practice as well as of individual works, both well known and obscure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aOpera and technologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aOpera and technologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aOperaxProduction and directionxHistoryy19th century. 0aOperaxProduction and directionxHistoryy20th century. 0aOperaxStage-setting and sceneryxHistoryy19th century. 0aOperaxStage-setting and sceneryxHistoryy20th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh  a19th century art.  a19th century music.  a19th century opera.  a19th century.  a20th century.  aacoustics.  aarchitecture.  aart history.  aartistic.  aaudiovisual.  acomposer.  acomposition.  afrench opera.  agerman opera.  ainventor.  amusic history.  amusical composition.  aopera.  aperformance art.  apop culture.  apopular culture.  apopular music.  astage crew.  atechnology.  atheatre.  awagner.  awagnerian technology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052027968140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966550/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY